snippet.textDisplay:
Bye-bye Honda, from F1 ... good riddance ...
What people don’t realize, and I corrected the publicity department when I worked at Siemens Solar, is that just because the end product doesn’t “pollute”, or have “emissions”, that doesn’t mean the manufacturing process also doesn’t pollute. It takes a tremendous amount of energy to melt silicon (melting point is around 1,420 °C), and grow a 35Kg single-crystal silicon ingot (105mm diameter by 1 meter long), in 48 hours. Think about it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Few points
1. If you ask any F1 fan what do they miss about F1, it's not the speed. It's the sound of V8 and V10 and battles. So speed flies out of the window.
2. The average F1 race is 305 km. The average Formula-E race is 4-5 km. Unless it's not hybrid, no way any electric car keeps the performance in the long run with current battery technologies.
3. Racing tournaments are a combination of speed and endurance. It's not about breaking lap records. No pure electric car has balls to compete in F1, Le Mans or NASCAR. And I personally enjoy the sound of engines and battles, not the vacuum cleaner sounds. Technologies will change the situation of course but there is still a way to go.

snippet.textDisplay: F1 has already lost almost all of my interest at this point so I don't really care unfortunately. Maybe they would gain it back if some of big manufacturers pulled out to go make their electric snow flake motors and f1 had to divert back to a modern, somewhat affordable version of a gasoline burning V8 like the Cosworth. But that's just my opinion. Very rarely do I watch current F1 races. As of lately I've been hooked on watching retro F1 and I love it! Mid 70s to late 80s is without a doubt the best era of the sport. The cars were crazy/awesome looking, sounded amazing, and very dangerous! They might not be as quick around the circuits as modern day F1 but, more entertaining to watch for me. The huge diversity of the cars and their power plants, and the courageous drivers that had the guts to pilot them has intrigued me for the past year or so. YouTube and Duke video have been great sources for plenty of insight into the "Dangerous years of Formula 1."
